\f0\fs24 \cf0 Famous Cases involving Digital Forensics\
\
\
Digital forensics increasingly plays a role in many law enforcement investigations, and in many high-profile cases it has provided key evidence that has been pivotal to solving the crime and saving lives.\
\
In 2005 investigators in Kansas used digital forensics to identify Dennis Rader as the BTK Serial Killer.  Rader had gone on a killing spree in the 1970s, eluded police for more than 30 years, then re-emerged, took another victim, and then sent police a floppy disk with a letter on it. On that disk forensic investigators found a deleted Microsoft Word file that contained metadata with the name "Dennis." The file also had to the Lutheran Church, where Rader was a Deacon. This was the break that police needed to gather more evidence and eventually arrest and convict the killer.\
\
